<p><div class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 135px">
	<a href="http://www.crunchbase.com/company/bigthink" title="Image representing Big Think as depicted in Cr..."><img title="Image representing Big Think as depicted in Cr..." src="http://www.crunchbase.com/assets/images/resized/0003/8089/38089v1-max-450x450.png" alt="Image representing Big Think as depicted in Cr..." width="135" height="95" /></a>
	<p class="wp-caption-text">Image via CrunchBase</p>
</div></p>
</div>
<p>Do you miss this blog? Well, you&#8217;re in luck. Starting September 12th, I&#8217;ll be starting a blog that covers much the same eclectic ground as the Fly Bottle over at <a href="http://bigthink.com/">Big Think</a>. It&#8217;ll be called The Moral Sciences Club, which I will explain in my first post there. I&#8217;ve been missing blogging about the range of stuff I used to blog about, especially philosophy, and I&#8217;m thrilled to have a chance to get back to it without having to worry much about hurting my thin, wavering freelancer&#8217;s bottom line. What about my evanescent Forbes blog, you ask? Forbes didn&#8217;t turn out to feel like a good fit for me, is all. But I&#8217;m much psyched about Big Think because, for one thing, it&#8217;s called &#8220;Big Think.&#8221; So there&#8217;s that. And I&#8217;ve been a fan of the site since its inception. Also, <em>Time </em>just named Big Think <a href="http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2087815_2087913_2087914,00.html ">the top &#8220;News &amp; Info&#8221; site of 2011</a>, and here&#8217;s what they said:</p>
<blockquote><p>The thinking at <a href="http://bigthink.com/" target="_blank">Big Think</a> is big indeed. This blog and video site covers, well, the world: arts, business, science, history and much more. Resident big thinkers such as futurist Ray Kurzweil and distinguished guests tackle the topics seriously, and counterintuitive notions and outright heresy are welcome. (One post <a href="http://bigthink.com/ideas/39548" target="_blank">speculated that there&#8217;s a 20% chance that we&#8217;re all part of an elaborate computer simulation from the future.</a>) It&#8217;s a great place to go to challenge your preconceived notions and recharge your mental batteries.</p></blockquote>
<p>Sounds like a great thing to be a part of, no?</p>
<p>This blog over the next few months will largely consist of posts pointing to my Big Think posts, the occasional sketch, and perhaps the odd, loose thought. And then we&#8217;ll see. Politics blogging at <em>The Economist</em> will proceed as usual.</p>
