<a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/jbjC13Ylmc7uiPXfEOOx2anRSKg/1/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/jbjC13Ylmc7uiPXfEOOx2anRSKg/1/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/willwilkinson/VeUZ/~4/_lakyTyIhtY" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded><description>Two new ones, of a Romney and a Perry supporter, went online at The Atlantic Thursday. Here are bigger versions (click to enlarge). And please click through to the slideshow to read their reasons for supporting their fave candidate (and to support this project!). &amp;#160;</description><thr:total xmlns:thr="http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0">0</thr:total><feedburner:origLink>http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/2011/08/20/more-sketches-of-iowa-republicans/</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>Ames Straw Poll Sketches</title><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/willwilkinson/VeUZ/~3/e6c_SFDSsks/</link><category>Filthy Non-theoretical Politics</category><category>Wilkinsketch</category><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Will Wilkinson</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 16 Aug 2011 10:33:16 PDT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/?p=5398</guid><content:encoded xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><![CDATA[<p></p><p>I went to the Ames Straw poll on Saturday, completely ignored the speeches and spent the whole time interviewing Iowans about which candidates they were supporting and why. On Sunday I made these five pen, ink, and watercolor sketches, which<a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2011/08/faces-of-iowa-sketches-from-the-ames-straw-poll/243618/"> the <em>Atlantic </em>made into a slideshow</a> along with excerpts from the interviews. I wish I could have included my Romney, Palin, and McCottter supporters, but there&#8217;s just not enough time in a single Sunday. Anyway, I&#8217;ve been wanting to get some illustration work, so I was pretty excited that the <em>Atlantic </em>was game. Check out <a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2011/08/faces-of-iowa-sketches-from-the-ames-straw-poll/243618/">the official slideshow</a> to read what these folks had to say. And <a href="https://picasaweb.google.com/118118984667460138733/AmesStrawPollSketchs?feat=flashalbum#slideshow/5641500408530803138">here&#8217;s the sketches again at something close to full size</a>.</p>

<p><a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/agKGr9vXjFXxN5vVhlL1N3C3GmE/0/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/agKGr9vXjFXxN5vVhlL1N3C3GmE/0/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a><br/>
<a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/agKGr9vXjFXxN5vVhlL1N3C3GmE/1/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/agKGr9vXjFXxN5vVhlL1N3C3GmE/1/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/willwilkinson/VeUZ/~4/e6c_SFDSsks" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded><description>I went to the Ames Straw poll on Saturday, completely ignored the speeches and spent the whole time interviewing Iowans about which candidates they were supporting and why. On Sunday I made these five pen, ink, and watercolor sketches, which the Atlantic made into a slideshow along with excerpts from the interviews. I wish I could [...]</description><thr:total xmlns:thr="http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0">1</thr:total><feedburner:origLink>http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/2011/08/16/ames-straw-poll-sketches/</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>Thank You for Your Service!</title><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/willwilkinson/VeUZ/~3/GA4zQAq-5xg/</link><category>Decency</category><category>War</category><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Will Wilkinson</dc:creator><pubDate>Mon, 04 Jul 2011 13:26:48 PDT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/?p=5385</guid><content:encoded xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><![CDATA[<p></p><p>Americans,<a href="http://www.facebook.com/teambachmann/posts/247005458643081"> here&#8217;s</a> Michele Bachmann&#8217;s message to you on Independence Day.</p>
<p><iframe width="450" height="286" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/abWUOu1YZ-U" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p>The task of &#8220;showing your thanks for our military men and women who protect&#8221; our freedoms brought to mind &#8220;<a href="http://www.newyorker.com/fiction/features/2011/06/13/110613fi_fiction_saunders?currentPage=all">Home</a>,&#8221; a funny, heartbreaking, damning George Saunders story I read yesterday in <em>The New Yorker</em>&#8216;s June fiction issue.  Excerpt:</p>
<blockquote><p>“I’ve been away a long time,” I said.</p>
<p>“Welcome back,” the first kid said.</p>
<p>“Where were you?” the second one said.</p>
<p>“At the war,” I said, in the most insulting voice I could muster. “Maybe you’ve heard of it?”</p>
<p>“I have,” the first one said respectfully. “Thank you for your service.”</p>
<p>“Which one?” the second one said. “Aren’t there two?”</p>
<p>“Didn’t they just call one off?” the first one said.</p>
<p>“My cousin’s there,” the second said. “At one of them. At least I think he is. I know he was supposed to go. We were never that close.”</p>
<p>“Anyway, thanks,” the first one said, and put out his hand, and I shook it.</p>
<p>“I wasn’t for it,” the second one said. “But I know it wasn’t your deal.”</p>
<p>“Well,” I said. “It kind of was.”</p>
<p>“You <em>weren’t</em> for it or <em>aren’t</em> for it?” the first said to the second.</p>
<p>“Both,” the second one said. “Although is it still going?”</p>
<p>“Which one?” the first one said.</p>
<p>“Is the one you were at still going?” the second one asked me.</p>
<p>“Yes,” I said.</p>
<p>“Better or worse, do you think?” the first one said. “Like, in your view, are we winning? Oh, what am I doing? I don’t actually care, that’s what’s so funny about it!”</p>
<p>“Anyway,” the second one said, and held out his hand, and I shook it.</p></blockquote>
<p>Read it all the way to the end.</p>
<p>This morning, on the local news, I learned about <a href="http://blogs.desmoinesregister.com/dmr/index.php/2011/07/03/officials-still-investigating-iowa-soldiers-death/">this</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p>Capt. Matthew Nielson, 27, of Jefferson died June 29, in Badrah, Iraq. He was killed by indirect fire attack while on duty in Iraq, Iowa National Guard officials said in a news release issued Sunday.</p></blockquote>
<p>Nielson was UNI grad, like me. Like me, he worked in a grocery store as a high-school student. He died in the course of an unjust war that has nothing do with protecting our freedom. Had I been born a decade later, he could have been me. It makes me sick to think about. Would his life have been wasted like this if Americans did not so strenuously insist on lying to one another about what it is our military men and women really do? Who does it help to continue to so effusively thank Matthew Nielson&#8217;s luckier comrades for their service and our freedom? Our gratitude is a rain of grenades over the senior high. Bright-eyed American boys and girls stare smiling down the smoking barrel of our thanks, dying to please.</p>

<p><a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/Rl6QqU2gkkHQYO6PBIQpiJ5iGRU/0/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/Rl6QqU2gkkHQYO6PBIQpiJ5iGRU/0/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a><br/>
<a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/Rl6QqU2gkkHQYO6PBIQpiJ5iGRU/1/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/Rl6QqU2gkkHQYO6PBIQpiJ5iGRU/1/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/willwilkinson/VeUZ/~4/GA4zQAq-5xg" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded><description>Americans, here&amp;#8217;s Michele Bachmann&amp;#8217;s message to you on Independence Day. The task of &amp;#8220;showing your thanks for our military men and women who protect&amp;#8221; our freedoms brought to mind &amp;#8220;Home,&amp;#8221; a funny, heartbreaking, damning George Saunders story I read yesterday in The New Yorker&amp;#8216;s June fiction issue.  Excerpt: “I’ve been away a long time,” I said. “Welcome [...]</description><thr:total xmlns:thr="http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0">11</thr:total><feedburner:origLink>http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/2011/07/04/thank-you-for-your-service/</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>Herman Cain in Marshalltown</title><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/willwilkinson/VeUZ/~3/tkvf3wt3hoI/</link><category>Filthy Non-theoretical Politics</category><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Will Wilkinson</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 30 Aug 2011 21:17:49 PDT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/?p=5379</guid><content:encoded xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><![CDATA[<p></p><p><div id="attachment_5381" class="wp-caption alignright" style="width: 300px">
	<a href="http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/DSCN0081.jpg" rel="shadowbox[sbpost-5379];player=img;" title="hermancainmarshalltown"><img class="size-medium wp-image-5381" title="hermancainmarshalltown" src="http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/DSCN0081-300x225.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a>
	<p class="wp-caption-text">Herman Cain talks to a firefighter from Clive</p>
</div></p>
<p>A short piece I wrote on Herman Cain&#8217;s visit to a small tea party event in my hometown Wednesday is now <a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2011/06/herman-cain-in-iowa-an-all-business-tea-party-pitch/240983/">online at <em>The Atlantic</em></a>. This is my favorite part:</p>
<blockquote><p>At about noon, Cain alights from a sleek black sedan outside Legends, where he is greeted in the drizzle by a smattering of journalists. Before heading into the restaurant to address the expectant room, a Swiss television crew and a few reporters are ushered with Cain up the steps of an aging Holiday Rambler motor home parked nearby. The middle third of the &#8220;bus&#8221; is covered in a giant, jumbled, color decal that reads &#8220;Return to a Golden Foundation,&#8221; &#8220;Train the Tea Party,&#8221; and &#8220;www.teapartybustour.com&#8221; in big block letters above logos for the tour&#8217;s sponsors&#8211;Iowa Tea Party, Gold Standard 2012, Leadership Institute, Tea Party Review&#8211;all printed atop a misty image of Old Glory superimposed over a parchment Constitution turned at 45 degrees. &#8220;People&#8221; of &#8220;We the People&#8221; is divided by the support post of a retracted retractable awning. The Holiday Rambler is fired up and taken for a slow spin around the WalMart lot and its various frontage and access roads, presumably so Swiss TV viewers can see Cain fielding questions while something like scenery slides by in a blur behind him, as if chatting amiably with newsmen while crisscrossing Iowa in a used recreational vehicle is something Herman Cain actually does.</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/NRC7WPdND_EUcHDgUj-9jh_FF5w/0/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/NRC7WPdND_EUcHDgUj-9jh_FF5w/0/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a><br/>
<a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/NRC7WPdND_EUcHDgUj-9jh_FF5w/1/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/NRC7WPdND_EUcHDgUj-9jh_FF5w/1/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/willwilkinson/VeUZ/~4/tkvf3wt3hoI" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded><description>A short piece I wrote on Herman Cain&amp;#8217;s visit to a small tea party event in my hometown Wednesday is now online at The Atlantic. This is my favorite part: At about noon, Cain alights from a sleek black sedan outside Legends, where he is greeted in the drizzle by a smattering of journalists. Before heading [...]</description><thr:total xmlns:thr="http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0">1</thr:total><feedburner:origLink>http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/2011/06/24/herman-cain-in-marshalltown/</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>Getting Money Out of Politics</title><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/willwilkinson/VeUZ/~3/CyRKowDVoNA/</link><category>Individualism</category><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Will Wilkinson</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 14 Jun 2011 14:37:13 PDT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/?p=5375</guid><content:encoded xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><![CDATA[<p></p><p>What are your favorite ideas for reducing the influence of campaign cash on legislators <em>other than </em>limiting legislative power and discretion, placing more restrictions on direct or indirect donations to campaigns, or socializing campaign finance altogether. Here&#8217;s what I&#8217;ve got so far:</p>
<ul>
<li>Much longer terms with no chance for re-election.</li>
<li>Very generous pensions for ex-legislators</li>
<li>Prohibition on ex-legislators accepting compensated employment or even unpaid advisory positions within 10, 15, 20, or whatever years after retirement from congress</li>
<li>Prohibition on current or ex-legislators owning stocks, bonds, etc.</li>
<li>Extremely high-prestige automatic membership in posh post-legislative body, e.g., The American Academy of Exalted Deliberation in the Public Interest, the proceedings and findings of which are treated with the utmost interest and respect.</li>
<li>Nobel-like large cash prize and title awarded to one especially exceptional legislator upon retirement (conferred by the AAEDPI, say).</li>
</ul>
<p>See what I&#8217;m after? Dazzle me, public choice folks!</p>

<p><a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/rT6pHFS3Vd_R803FTFhD4txRauM/0/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/rT6pHFS3Vd_R803FTFhD4txRauM/0/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a><br/>
<a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/rT6pHFS3Vd_R803FTFhD4txRauM/1/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/rT6pHFS3Vd_R803FTFhD4txRauM/1/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/willwilkinson/VeUZ/~4/CyRKowDVoNA" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded><description>What are your favorite ideas for reducing the influence of campaign cash on legislators other than limiting legislative power and discretion, placing more restrictions on direct or indirect donations to campaigns, or socializing campaign finance altogether. Here&amp;#8217;s what I&amp;#8217;ve got so far: Much longer terms with no chance for re-election. Very generous pensions for ex-legislators [...]</description><thr:total xmlns:thr="http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0">63</thr:total><feedburner:origLink>http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/2011/06/14/getting-money-out-of-politics/</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>Help! Elite Influence and Public Opinion</title><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/willwilkinson/VeUZ/~3/kR8fY1RYG9c/</link><category>Public Opinion</category><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Will Wilkinson</dc:creator><pubDate>Sun, 05 Jun 2011 11:06:31 PDT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/?p=5368</guid><content:encoded xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><![CDATA[<p></p><p>O&#8217; Holy Internet, I beseech thee: whither the superior overview of state-of-the-art political science on the matter of elite influence on public opinion?</p>

<p><a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/XY0Q_cCVKthb7fEKfZ5boS95P6g/0/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/XY0Q_cCVKthb7fEKfZ5boS95P6g/0/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a><br/>
<a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/XY0Q_cCVKthb7fEKfZ5boS95P6g/1/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/XY0Q_cCVKthb7fEKfZ5boS95P6g/1/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/willwilkinson/VeUZ/~4/kR8fY1RYG9c" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded><description>O&amp;#8217; Holy Internet, I beseech thee: whither the superior overview of state-of-the-art political science on the matter of elite influence on public opinion?</description><thr:total xmlns:thr="http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0">9</thr:total><feedburner:origLink>http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/2011/06/05/help-elite-influence-and-public-opinion/</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>Neurodiversity and Writing Advice</title><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/willwilkinson/VeUZ/~3/_prdU2ef-Hs/</link><category>Human Nature</category><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Will Wilkinson</dc:creator><pubDate>Thu, 02 Jun 2011 11:37:15 PDT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/?p=5366</guid><content:encoded xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><![CDATA[<p></p><p>Steve Silberman is writing a book on neurodiversity, a subject I&#8217;m deeply interested in. He&#8217;s been having a bit of anxiety about it. He&#8217;s written feature articles before, but never a book. So he solicited advice from a bunch of experienced writers and has <a href="http://blogs.plos.org/neurotribes/2011/06/02/practical-tips-on-writing-a-book-from-22-brilliant-authors/">shared what they shared with him</a>. It&#8217;s interesting to read. Of course, a lot of it is mostly irrelevant to me, and probably to Silberman, because of Silberman&#8217;s subject, neurodiversity. The uselessness of a lot of advice, or the neuro-relativity of usefulness, seems to me a pretty straightforward implication of the plurality of attentional, creative, and cognitive styles, and I found it interesting that someone writing specifically about diverse kinds of minds didn&#8217;t note this in presenting a bunch of advice about how to do something as neurologically demanding as book-writing. There&#8217;s an obvious selection-effect problem here. Most book-writing advice is going to comes from people who are able to successfully apply standard book-writing advice. But I don&#8217;t need book-writing advice from those people. I need to know what works for people with a mind like mine. Maybe nothing works. Maybe the best advice for people like me is: don&#8217;t try to write a book, you flake. Or: if you insist, you will suffer, and it may or may not be worth it.</p>

<p><a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/iQtVcVcWccL5u5SO7YF-ed4cJRs/0/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/iQtVcVcWccL5u5SO7YF-ed4cJRs/0/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a><br/>
<a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/iQtVcVcWccL5u5SO7YF-ed4cJRs/1/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/iQtVcVcWccL5u5SO7YF-ed4cJRs/1/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a></p><img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/willwilkinson/VeUZ/~4/_prdU2ef-Hs" height="1" width="1"/>]]></content:encoded><description>Steve Silberman is writing a book on neurodiversity, a subject I&amp;#8217;m deeply interested in. He&amp;#8217;s been having a bit of anxiety about it. He&amp;#8217;s written feature articles before, but never a book. So he solicited advice from a bunch of experienced writers and has shared what they shared with him. It&amp;#8217;s interesting to read. Of [...]</description><thr:total xmlns:thr="http://purl.org/syndication/thread/1.0">9</thr:total><feedburner:origLink>http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/2011/06/02/neurodiversity-and-writing-advice/</feedburner:origLink></item><item><title>So, This Is Nice</title><link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/willwilkinson/VeUZ/~3/jzVNX8maT7U/</link><category>Whatever</category><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Will Wilkinson</dc:creator><pubDate>Fri, 06 May 2011 09:21:39 PDT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.willwilkinson.net/flybottle/?p=5360</guid><content:encoded xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"><![CDATA[<p></p><p>From <a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2011/05/nearly-100-fantastic-pieces-of-journalism/238230/">Conor Friedersdorf&#8217;s list</a> of 2010&#8242;s best journalism at <em>The Atlantic</em>:</p>
<blockquote><p><strong>BLOGGERS OF THE YEAR</strong></p></blockquote>
<blockquote><p>- In lively, exquisitely crafted prose, Will Wilkinson offered posts at <a href="http://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica">Democracy In America</a> that managed a rare trifecta: they were provocative, logically sound, and infused with razor sharp wit.</p>
<p>- <a href="http://www.salon.com/news/opinion/glenn_greenwald/index.html">Glenn Greenwald</a>, <a href="http://www.juliansanchez.com/">Julian Sanchez</a>, <a href="http://www.theagitator.com/">Radley Balko</a> and <a href="http://prospect.org/csnc/blogs/adam_serwer">Adam Serwer</a> for their vital work on civil liberties.</p>
<p>- Joe Posnanski for his delightful <a href="http://joeposnanski.blogspot.com/">sports blog</a>.</p></blockquote>
<p>Gosh. And I&#8217;m honored to be included among the likes of Greenwald, Serwer and my old liberty-loving friends, Sanchez and Balko. I just gave Joe Posnanki a look-see, and I find it&#8217;s mostly baseball, which brings to mind this exchange between Lewis &#8220;Teabag&#8221; Miner, the narrator, and Principal Fontana from Sam Lipsyte&#8217;s ridiculous novel <em><a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/0312424183/ref=as_li_ss_til?tag=theflybottle-20&amp;camp=213381&amp;creative=390973&amp;linkCode=as4&amp;creativeASIN=0312424183&amp;adid=0AXQ63TEEW1HWFNV53M9&amp;">Homeland</a></em>, which I recommend if you like drugs, jokes, self-abuse, feeling terrible about high school, <em>tour de force</em> ranting, and/or the sounds of words.</p>
<blockquote><p>&#8220;I didn&#8217;t know you followed baseball&#8221;</p>
<p>&#8220;I don&#8217;t. It&#8217;s a load of pseudopoetic crap, boring as hell. It was invented so frustrated intellectuals could pine for their daddies without appearing too unmanly.</p>
<p>&#8220;I like baseball,&#8221; I said.</p>
<p>I&#8217;m just kidding, buddy. Of course I like baseball. But I like french fries dipped in melon juice and giving it to Loretta from behind more.&#8221;</p>
<p>&#8220;I should get going,&#8221; I said.</p>
<p>&#8220;Live, Miner. There&#8217;s nothing to it. It&#8217;s not original. Just necessary&#8221;</p>
<p>I&#8217;d had enough of Fontana, Catamounts. Sometimes the idea of a man is sufficient. Fontana was a fine enough notion for a man, but to see him here, sick eyes afire in hood shadow, to listen to his lectures on the art of living, it was more than I could stand.</p>
<p>I stood.</p>
<p>&#8220;Where are you going?&#8221;</p>
<p>&#8220;There&#8217;s something I&#8217;ve got to do,&#8221; I said. &#8220;Be careful.&#8221;</p>
<p>Fontana gazed out in reverie upon his car.</p>
<p>&#8220;Maybe I don&#8217;t like baseball,&#8221; he said. &#8220;I can&#8217;t decide.&#8221;</p></blockquote>
<p>I can&#8217;t decide either. But I&#8217;m sure Conor is a prince among men. <a href="http://letterly.net/TheBestOfJournalism">Subscribe to his Best of Journalism email newsletter</a>.</p>

<p><a href="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/Pfw80P0YDx7tUOsPmfAe1GuuT7w/0/da"><img src="http://feedads.g.doubleclick.net/~a/Pfw80P0YDx7tUOsPmfAe1GuuT7w/0/di" border="0" ismap="true"></img></a><br/>
